on, and schooling, are fraught with distractions and uncertainties. Paying special attention to this marginalized group, this book investigates the role of parental migration and the left-behind status in shaping Chinese family dynamics and children’s general wellbeing, including their school performance, delinquency, resilience, feelings of ambiguous loss, and other psychological problems. Blending theory, empirical research, and real-world interviews with left-behind children, China's Left-Behind Children provides a uniquely close look at these children's lives while also providing the larger national context that defines and shapes their everyday lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChildren of single parentszChina. 0aChildrenzChinaxSocial conditions. 0aRural-urban migrationzChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  achina, families, migration, urbanization, abandonment, culture, class, industrialization, children, left-behind children, sociology, rural, caretakers, grandparents, support network, long-distance relationship.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079131040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197883717140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978837171423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978837171/original  a978-3-11-079131-0  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles